I'm not putting down games which are just purely about mechanical advancement,

254
00:10:51,756 --> 00:10:55,520
that's a lot of fun as well, but there are other things we can do to change internally.

255
00:10:57,142 --> 00:11:01,246
So that change must happen in some kind. But how do we apply all this kind of stuff to games?

256
00:11:01,507 --> 00:11:05,151
Well, we might not think of Tetris as a game with the greatest of plots.

257
00:11:06,324 --> 00:11:08,525
but it really does follow these kind of things pretty well.

258
00:11:09,186 --> 00:11:11,167
It's a very, very compelling player experience.

259
00:11:11,507 --> 00:11:12,347
Now if we think about this,

260
00:11:12,387 --> 00:11:13,768
if we think about the tension arc

261
00:11:13,788 --> 00:11:15,189
that we go through when we're playing this,

262
00:11:15,769 --> 00:11:17,950
it fits that flow thing, it fits that tension arc.

263
00:11:18,551 --> 00:11:20,612
And the player has both external and internal goals.

264
00:11:20,892 --> 00:11:22,633
We have the scores as an external goal,

265
00:11:22,653 --> 00:11:23,753
and we have that internal goal,

266
00:11:23,793 --> 00:11:25,654
which is kind of a desire for order.

267
00:11:26,455 --> 00:11:28,796
Tetris is driven by the thing that we like the world

268
00:11:28,836 --> 00:11:30,197
to be slightly neater than it is.

269
00:11:31,325 --> 00:11:35,109
And this is a tiny place where maybe, just maybe, we'll succeed in making it happen.

270
00:11:35,910 --> 00:11:37,831
And it's always a tragedy, because we always fail.

271
00:11:40,294 --> 00:11:44,277
But I think that internal goal is a really powerful part of the lasting appeal of Tetris.

272
00:11:44,657 --> 00:11:47,780
That sense of desiring order and it always chasing away from us.

273
00:11:47,800 --> 00:11:53,125
That's a very human experience, and I think that's one of the reasons it works as such an enduring appeal for us.

274
00:11:54,893 --> 00:11:56,634
So if you add that quickly into our diagram there,

275
00:11:56,674 --> 00:12:00,036
we have the external motivation is looking for change,

276
00:12:00,096 --> 00:12:01,737
usually expressed through very direct verbs

277
00:12:01,757 --> 00:12:03,558
like save and find and things like that.

278
00:12:03,938 --> 00:12:06,919
And internal is about overcoming or coming to terms with.

279
00:12:10,101 --> 00:12:11,922
So, let's move on to plot structure.

280
00:12:14,145 --> 00:12:15,746
You've got your goals for your player character,

281
00:12:15,766 --> 00:12:17,447
your external, internal motivations there.

282
00:12:18,407 --> 00:12:19,908
Now we need a well-structured series of events

283
00:12:19,948 --> 00:12:21,269
through which change will happen.

284
00:12:22,129 --> 00:12:24,010
The external goals are just a desire.

285
00:12:24,590 --> 00:12:26,291
We need the plot to make that change happen.

286
00:12:26,852 --> 00:12:29,613
So a plot controls the speed of progress

287
00:12:29,653 --> 00:12:31,494
through the tension arc of the experience.

288
00:12:31,514 --> 00:12:33,255
And so I'm gonna be talking a little bit more in detail

289
00:12:33,275 --> 00:12:34,296
about how this plot works.

290
00:12:35,236 --> 00:12:38,818
So, start your story before the big events begin.

291
00:12:39,699 --> 00:12:42,460
This is one thing that a lot of games fail to do properly.

292
00:12:43,814 --> 00:12:46,816
By this I mean you don't start your story with,

293
00:12:46,836 --> 00:12:47,636
you're a wizard, Harry.

294
00:12:48,837 --> 00:12:51,298
You have this whole part of meeting the Dursleys,

295
00:12:51,318 --> 00:12:54,499
you have his childhood, his normal everyday life

296
00:12:54,660 --> 00:13:00,943
outside of the wizard world before you see Hagrid come in,

297
00:13:00,983 --> 00:13:02,764
before you experience the world of magic.

298
00:13:03,204 --> 00:13:05,405
Because the world of magic by itself means nothing

299
00:13:05,805 --> 00:13:08,126
unless it's contrasted by the world of the ordinary.

300
00:13:09,315 --> 00:13:12,497
We see this sometimes in games, and when we do, it's very powerful.

301
00:13:12,918 --> 00:13:15,639
Prince of Persia, Sands of Time is one of my favorite storytelling games.

302
00:13:15,659 --> 00:13:18,721
And it's got a little snatch of normality at the very beginning of it.

303
00:13:18,982 --> 00:13:20,463
It's beautiful, really lovely game.

304
00:13:21,383 --> 00:13:24,325
So you set up your character, the situation, and the basic rules of this.

305
00:13:24,785 --> 00:13:26,526
This is otherwise known as a tutorial mission.

306
00:13:27,287 --> 00:13:29,448
You can do it that way. You can literally do it.

307
00:13:29,748 --> 00:13:30,749
Set it in a normal world.

308
00:13:31,029 --> 00:13:33,211
Call of Duty sometimes does this, that you train on the base

309
00:13:33,271 --> 00:13:37,193
before you go and shoot people who are ideologically opposed to you.

310
00:13:40,749 --> 00:13:44,353
So you, I wasn't going to do politics.

311
00:13:45,033 --> 00:13:46,195
I said I wouldn't.

312
00:13:46,655 --> 00:13:48,437
So start your story before the events begin.

313
00:13:48,957 --> 00:13:50,278
It's really important to build empathy

314
00:13:50,299 --> 00:13:51,500
with your characters if possible.

315
00:13:51,900 --> 00:13:53,962
So we want the character to overcome

316
00:13:54,002 --> 00:13:54,903
the challenges ahead of us.

317
00:13:55,283 --> 00:13:57,365
Now a really great example of this I think is Firewatch.

318
00:13:57,385 --> 00:13:59,127
I think Firewatch did beautiful work with this.

319
00:13:59,528 --> 00:14:01,309
So before we reach the lake in Firewatch,

320
00:14:01,329 --> 00:14:03,271
which is really when the story begins to kick off

321
00:14:03,291 --> 00:14:04,112
and that tension starts.

322
00:14:04,612 --> 00:14:08,436
We know a lot about Harry, we know about his external and internal motivations

323
00:14:08,796 --> 00:14:12,719
and the story begins with that moment there, that his external motivation is really

324
00:14:13,080 --> 00:14:17,704
kicked off by, there's trouble in this park. So we've got this internal stuff,

325
00:14:17,744 --> 00:14:19,165
that growth, that need to escape

326
00:14:19,785 --> 00:14:24,349
and we know at some point he's going to have to go back. It's a nice setup and it makes

327
00:14:24,389 --> 00:14:27,612
the rest the game powerful. If we just started with that confrontation with the

328
00:14:28,173 --> 00:14:31,996
teenage woman, it probably wouldn't work so well.

329
00:14:33,698 --> 00:14:35,479
And then we have what we call the inciting incident.

330
00:14:36,340 --> 00:14:37,861
So now your player character knows their place

331
00:14:37,881 --> 00:14:39,243
in the world, we can start to set up

332
00:14:39,263 --> 00:14:40,103
the challenges for them.

333
00:14:40,564 --> 00:14:43,046
So we increase the narrative or mechanical tension here,

334
00:14:43,546 --> 00:14:45,288
and we add the antagonist or the enemies,

335
00:14:45,628 --> 00:14:48,270
the risk, or we break the usual situation.

336
00:14:48,330 --> 00:14:49,912
Something which was normal and everyday

337
00:14:50,292 --> 00:14:51,293
becomes less normal.

338
00:14:51,313 --> 00:14:52,494
Suddenly it stops working.

339
00:14:53,134 --> 00:14:54,335
See this in the Stanley parable,

340
00:14:54,375 --> 00:14:55,476
the button stops going.

341
00:14:58,047 --> 00:15:00,849
Overcoming this problem is usually the external motivation of your plot.

342
00:15:01,049 --> 00:15:05,072
Trying to find the source of that problem and bring it back into normality

343
00:15:05,112 --> 00:15:06,753
is usually what drives your main character.

344
00:15:08,394 --> 00:15:11,597
But to begin with, the player character avoids the problem.

345
00:15:11,917 --> 00:15:14,198
The player doesn't usually go straight to attacking the problem,

346
00:15:14,218 --> 00:15:17,141
they'll either explore their abilities, explore the world,

347
00:15:17,181 --> 00:15:19,482
they'll avoid the big issue that's facing them,

348
00:15:19,822 --> 00:15:21,624
or they'll have some smaller battles along the way.

349
00:15:22,587 --> 00:15:26,750
So in VVVVVV, which I shall call Spikes from now on,

350
00:15:27,390 --> 00:15:28,691
so in Spikes, the player character

351
00:15:28,731 --> 00:15:29,932
has to rescue their colleagues.

352
00:15:31,253 --> 00:15:32,454
It's a really lovely little game.

353
00:15:32,914 --> 00:15:34,215
It reminds me a lot of Jet Set William.

354
00:15:34,555 --> 00:15:36,797
It's really a lovely little game, it's very, very fun.

355
00:15:37,277 --> 00:15:40,019
But to begin with, basically the player wanders aimlessly.

356
00:15:40,959 --> 00:15:41,960
Really, that's what you do.

357
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:43,021
You don't, you're not setting off,

358
00:15:43,241 --> 00:15:44,602
ah, I shall find everybody immediately.

359
00:15:44,622 --> 00:15:46,763
No, you go off and play and you see

360
00:15:46,804 --> 00:15:48,204
what the kind of puzzles are in the world.

361
00:15:49,223 --> 00:15:52,946
Now after a little while of exploration, they make a choice to act with intention.

362
00:15:53,826 --> 00:15:56,048
After a while the player feels like they know the territory enough to make that

363
00:15:56,328 --> 00:15:59,411
focused choice to act, or there's no choice left but to act.

364
00:15:59,471 --> 00:16:02,893
You've done all the sub-missions, you have to go do a story one.

365
00:16:04,755 --> 00:16:07,397
In Spikes that means basically, I better use the map more.

366
00:16:08,548 --> 00:16:10,149
If you ever play the game, eventually you kind of go,

367
00:16:10,169 --> 00:16:11,209
oh yeah, I'm lost, okay.

368
00:16:12,410 --> 00:16:13,490
What is this flashing elephant?

369
00:16:14,630 --> 00:16:16,271
They engage with the external objective

370
00:16:16,451 --> 00:16:18,512
of the story or the world that's ahead of them.

371
00:16:18,812 --> 00:16:21,173
And that's when they really begin to kind of get into this.

372
00:16:22,174 --> 00:16:23,334
But as they get further into it,

373
00:16:23,374 --> 00:16:24,695
the complexity begins to increase.

374
00:16:25,295 --> 00:16:28,256
The abilities seem less effective, maybe.

375
00:16:28,717 --> 00:16:30,737
New enemies are added, which are more challenging.

376
00:16:31,158 --> 00:16:34,419
New story elements show that things were not so simple

377
00:16:34,459 --> 00:16:35,559
as we thought they were to begin with.

378
00:16:36,493 --> 00:16:37,994
And I think Tetris is a masterpiece

379
00:16:38,374 --> 00:16:39,655
because of exactly this moment.

380
00:16:44,577 --> 00:16:46,158
Suddenly complexity has increased.

381
00:16:47,579 --> 00:16:48,980
And suddenly we know that there's gonna be

382
00:16:49,020 --> 00:16:50,300
difficulty ahead and we're gonna have to,

383
00:16:50,621 --> 00:16:52,722
our strategy of just piling things on top of each other

384
00:16:52,762 --> 00:16:54,963
is now a strategy of slipping things underneath

385
00:16:55,083 --> 00:16:57,324
just about quickly, move down, oh no.

386
00:16:58,425 --> 00:16:59,745
Suddenly the complexity has increased

387
00:16:59,765 --> 00:17:01,586
and this is a storytelling moment in itself.

388
00:17:03,166 --> 00:17:05,569
I think the complexity has to increase to make the experience compelling,

389
00:17:05,609 --> 00:17:08,452
otherwise it stays at this kind of flat level, the tension doesn't change.

390
00:17:09,533 --> 00:17:13,117
So that complexity can change through narrative terms, mechanical terms, or through both.

391
00:17:13,837 --> 00:17:17,081
I like both, if you can, but you can just do it with narrative.

392
00:17:17,862 --> 00:17:20,665
I think that's a really valid way of doing it, if you're making purely narrative games.

393
00:17:24,489 --> 00:17:26,730
So in Virginia, we see divisions between the protagonists

394
00:17:26,890 --> 00:17:29,352
and the dreams begin to call some of reality into question.

395
00:17:29,372 --> 00:17:32,195
And this is a complexification of the everyday setting

396
00:17:32,215 --> 00:17:33,155
that we've gone into.

397
00:17:34,516 --> 00:17:36,978
In Firewatch, an extra layer of conspiracy is added.

398
00:17:37,299 --> 00:17:38,460
There's not just missing women,

399
00:17:38,480 --> 00:17:40,041
there's some other stuff going on in the park

400
00:17:40,061 --> 00:17:42,943
and it all gets a bit, ooh, it's cool, I love that game.

401
00:17:43,604 --> 00:17:44,705
In my own game, Fragments of Him,

402
00:17:45,585 --> 00:17:46,846
Will's kind of been trying to build

403
00:17:46,886 --> 00:17:49,488
a big long-term relationship and halfway through,

404
00:17:49,989 --> 00:17:51,870
he begins to doubt whether he can stay in a relationship

405
00:17:51,890 --> 00:17:52,931
without hurting other people.

406
00:17:53,805 --> 00:17:58,640
It's a big doubtful moment and this is the low midpoint of most stories.

407
00:18:01,148 --> 00:18:03,711
So the first strategies and weapons are no longer enough usually.

408
00:18:04,011 --> 00:18:06,694
In shooters, new patterns and combinations of enemies are added.

409
00:18:07,575 --> 00:18:10,317
Something like Super Stardust tends to add in new things halfway through.

410
00:18:10,818 --> 00:18:13,600
Enemies use better targeting, more bullets or homing missiles.

411
00:18:14,541 --> 00:18:19,126
Enemies begin to get dangerous new abilities like moving faster or tracking you.

412
00:18:19,926 --> 00:18:23,750
In Left 4 Dead, you would not throw these things at the player as soon as they walk out the door.

413
00:18:24,827 --> 00:18:25,828
It's just natural, isn't it?

414
00:18:25,848 --> 00:18:26,568
And that's what I mean.

415
00:18:26,929 --> 00:18:28,650
Some of these patterns are intuitive to us.

416
00:18:29,150 --> 00:18:30,591
We just know it wouldn't be a good idea.

417
00:18:31,672 --> 00:18:33,293
Then hope overcomes fear with some effort.

418
00:18:33,593 --> 00:18:35,034
Player finds new weapons or strategies

419
00:18:35,074 --> 00:18:35,874
to overcome the enemies.

420
00:18:36,255 --> 00:18:37,496
The external change happens.

421
00:18:37,536 --> 00:18:38,956
They get power-ups or grinding.

422
00:18:39,297 --> 00:18:42,079
This is kind of the weapon montage

423
00:18:42,119 --> 00:18:43,399
and the training montage in a film.

424
00:18:43,840 --> 00:18:45,401
They find the strength they never knew they had.

425
00:18:45,741 --> 00:18:47,402
They have that moment of internal change,

426
00:18:47,462 --> 00:18:49,323
which I think Life is Strange does so well

427
00:18:49,363 --> 00:18:50,584
with Kate's story.

428
00:18:52,151 --> 00:18:55,692
and the character learns to unite their skills and teams behind a single purpose.

429
00:18:56,233 --> 00:18:57,173
It has high risks.

430
00:18:57,953 --> 00:18:59,974
There's danger ahead now. Before it was just fun,

431
00:19:00,014 --> 00:19:02,235
but now there's danger in facing these things.

432
00:19:02,615 --> 00:19:04,216
But it is their only hope to continue.

433
00:19:06,957 --> 00:19:07,777
Guns. Lots of guns.

434
00:19:09,722 --> 00:19:10,923
And then we get to the black moment.

435
00:19:11,264 --> 00:19:13,085
All hopes of overcoming the problem are at risk.

436
00:19:13,345 --> 00:19:15,708
The final boss is killed, but it's not even his final form.

437
00:19:15,828 --> 00:19:18,310
Oh my God, it's this kind of moment

438
00:19:18,350 --> 00:19:20,512
that the escalating danger seems too much.

439
00:19:20,852 --> 00:19:22,394
And all the knowledge, the relationships,

440
00:19:22,414 --> 00:19:23,455
the strategies developed through

441
00:19:23,475 --> 00:19:24,516
the player character experience

442
00:19:24,876 --> 00:19:27,418
are needed to overcome this final challenge.

443
00:19:27,778 --> 00:19:31,322
The final choice, the heartbreaking relationships

444
00:19:31,362 --> 00:19:34,224
you've built along the way are all at risk now.

445
00:19:34,725 --> 00:19:36,486
And what choice will you make about the future?

446
00:19:38,086 --> 00:19:39,648
It's a powerful moment, the black moment.

447
00:19:40,288 --> 00:19:41,690
Very, very important in your story.

448
00:19:43,552 --> 00:19:45,574
And then, you end it as fast as possible.

449
00:19:46,235 --> 00:19:47,957
People often say, how long should my ending be?

450
00:19:47,997 --> 00:19:49,899
You say, you do it as quickly as you possibly can.

451
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:51,721
And you keep the ending neat and short,

452
00:19:51,781 --> 00:19:54,044
wrapping up as many of the threads as you possibly can,

453
00:19:54,484 --> 00:19:55,265
as easily as you can.

454
00:19:56,661 --> 00:19:58,663
So let's add all of that to our diagram.

455
00:19:58,943 --> 00:19:59,364
Okay.

456
00:20:00,244 --> 00:20:02,907
So we're gonna start off with our before it begins moment.

457
00:20:03,327 --> 00:20:04,949
We get to our inciting incident,

458
00:20:05,109 --> 00:20:06,731
where we kind of have a need for change.

459
00:20:07,231 --> 00:20:08,833
But the character kind of tries to avoid it,

460
00:20:08,873 --> 00:20:10,194
thinks it's somebody else's problem.

461
00:20:10,614 --> 00:20:11,775
And then it kind of gets that statement

462
00:20:11,795 --> 00:20:12,596
of external objective.

463
00:20:12,636 --> 00:20:13,977
Yes, I will face up to this.

464
00:20:14,017 --> 00:20:16,920
Yes, I will use the map more and find my colleagues.

465
00:20:17,839 --> 00:20:22,080
They try this, they try these kind of things and it's not really working.

466
00:20:22,140 --> 00:20:23,161
We get to the low midpoint.

467
00:20:23,441 --> 00:20:24,541
They're going to have to get better.

468
00:20:24,561 --> 00:20:26,842
They're going to have to find new ways of dealing with these kind of things.

469
00:20:27,482 --> 00:20:29,723
Training montage, people get to power up,

470
00:20:29,743 --> 00:20:32,244
people grind as their characters a little bit more to get the high things.

471
00:20:32,624 --> 00:20:34,584
We get some hope entering into the story.

472
00:20:34,925 --> 00:20:37,365
Maybe if I keep on doing this, if I get better at this game,

473
00:20:37,425 --> 00:20:38,546
I'll overcome these challenges.

474
00:20:39,638 --> 00:20:41,959
Then we get to this moment of building up,

475
00:20:42,139 --> 00:20:45,160
that everybody assembles behind this one plan

476
00:20:45,200 --> 00:20:46,300
which is gonna push us forward.

477
00:20:46,780 --> 00:20:48,580
When we reach the black moment where all is at risk,

478
00:20:48,980 --> 00:20:51,001
and maybe just with enough skill,

479
00:20:51,041 --> 00:20:53,421
with enough of the things that we saved along the way

480
00:20:53,461 --> 00:20:57,302
we can overcome, and we have the final satisfying conclusion.

481
00:20:58,342 --> 00:21:00,243
Cool, you may have noticed there's a bit missing

482
00:21:00,263 --> 00:21:01,063
at the beginning and the end there,

483
00:21:01,283 --> 00:21:02,623
because that's the model for most stories.

484
00:21:03,083 --> 00:21:04,344
As a player's character journey,

485
00:21:04,424 --> 00:21:05,924
this fits most strong experiences.

486
00:21:05,964 --> 00:21:07,764
A lot of films you see will follow this model

487
00:21:07,844 --> 00:21:08,705
pretty much exactly.

488
00:21:09,682 --> 00:21:12,445
It works on an intuitive and emotional level to feel very rewarding.

489
00:21:12,585 --> 00:21:15,888
But if you're making a thriller, an action or a horror story,

490
00:21:15,928 --> 00:21:17,710
you might want to add an extra little bit on there.

491
00:21:18,751 --> 00:21:20,132
Horror stories in particular do this one.

492
00:21:20,373 --> 00:21:22,835
There's an additional bit of structure you might want to consider adding at the very beginning,

493
00:21:22,855 --> 00:21:23,796
which is called the grabber.

494
00:21:24,216 --> 00:21:27,499
It's a burst of action or fear that promises future of the game

495
00:21:27,539 --> 00:21:29,481
and slows down before the inciting incident.

496
00:21:30,864 --> 00:21:33,945
So it's a way to let the player character know there's going to be excitement ahead

497
00:21:34,426 --> 00:21:36,367
and then you give them a bit of breathing space later on.

498
00:21:37,007 --> 00:21:41,310
For example, this is the Metroid games where you end up with loads of great powers at the beginning

499
00:21:41,330 --> 00:21:45,293
and then they take them away and kind of go, okay, let's let you build those up slowly now.

500
00:21:46,754 --> 00:21:50,656
Or the Goblet of Fire. It gets a moment of horror at the beginning

